    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-24T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-24T04:00:00-05:00" n="54"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d54">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/12386: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Finland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schoenfeld</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Helsinki</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-24T11:00:00+02:00"
                            >June 24, 1941—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>220. British Minister states that in response to his inquiry of Minister for
                    Foreign Affairs whether latter could “guarantee” neutrality of Finland in
                    Soviet-German war, Witting told him yesterday that no such guarantee was
                    possible but that it was firm purpose of Finnish Government to keep out of the
                    conflict and every effort would be made to do so. Soviet Minister yesterday told
                    Vereker that regular railroad traffic with Leningrad as well as the Russian
                    transit traffic with Hango continue.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schoenfeld</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
